eased February 2, 2026)\n\nOpenAI officially released a **standalone Codex desktop application for macOS** on February 2, 2026, specifically designed for macOS 14 and later systems. Here are the key features:\n\n### Core Agentic Coding Features:\n- **Multi-Agent Collaboration**: Supports multiple AI agents working in parallel on the same codebase without conflicts\n- **Agent Skills System**: First-class support for customizable \"Skills\" - specialized capabilities that can be assigned to different agents\n- **Automations**: Scheduled task execution capabilities for \"development-review-iteration\" workflows\n- **Multi-threaded Project Management**: Addresses context loss during task switching\n- **Work Tree Support**: Allows multiple AI agents to operate on the same code repository simultaneously\n- **Seamless Integration**: Automatically syncs with CLI and IDE plugin configurations\n\n### Development Focus:\nThe app focuses on \"agentic coding\" scenarios, providing developers with an AI agent-based intelligent programming collaboration environment. It's designed to shorten the development cycle from concept to executable software.\n\n## Xcode 26.3 Integration (Released February 3, 2026)\n\nSimultaneously, Apple released **Xcode 26.3** which introduces native agentic coding support:\n\n- Integrates both **OpenAI's Codex** and **Anthropic's Claude Agent**\n- Features **\"Vibe Coding\"** (intent-oriented programming) - developers describe requirements in natural language, and AI generates complete, runnable code\n- Testing showed that zero-experience users could build a functional Pomodoro timer app with notifications and settings in just two minutes\n- Supports visual interface analysis and Model Context Protocol (MCP)\n- AI agents can autonomously complete complex development tasks, make decisions based on project architecture, and break down tasks\n\n## Industry Context\n\nThe February 2026 releases represent a significant advancement in AI-assisted development, 